win32 11/11/2021 00:04
Does the OpenGL thing give you an error code of 0xC000001D?
00:05
That would indicate an illegal CPU instruction. I believe there is a Switch emulator that is known to do the same thing on Sandy Bridge and above.
00:09
That would be because of the usage of AVX/AVX2. As they use new registers, the OS needs to support context switching/saving/restoring the value of these registers to prevent register data corruption. If the right bits in the control registers are not set, AVX/AVX2 are disabled.
00:09
The same thing with SSE. So you can't use SSE properly on anything before Windows NT 4 SP5 or Windows 98 SE.
